<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN CEOS CALL FOR BETTER INVESTMENT ENVIRONMENT
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  May 4 (CNA) 05/04/07  22:28:51 (By T.C. Jiang)
</P>
<P>
Around 54.5 percent of Taiwan's top 1,000 enterprise CEOs urged
Taiwan's next president, to be elected in 2008, to first create a
business-friendly investment environment, according to the
results of a survey released Friday.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by the Commonwealth Magazine between
March 9 and April 11, with 352 valid questionnaires collected.
</P>
<P>
Around 52.3 percent of the CEOs polled said the new president
should engage in more open interaction with China, while 39.2
percent said the president should have a visionary development
plan, according to the survey results.
</P>
<P>
The total number of CEOs who are not happy with Taiwan's economy
reached 77 percent this year, the survey indicates, adding that
the percentage has been on the rise since 2004.
</P>
<P>
The respondents are not optimistic about Taiwan's economic
situation this year, with over 56.8 percent believing that
Taiwan's economic performance will remain the same and 25.1
percent worrying that Taiwans economic growth will drop from last
year, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
The ratios saw an increase from last year, according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 41.8 percent of the CEOs are most concerned about Taiwan's
declining competitiveness, 36.6 percent are worried that the room
for growth is limited, while 30.1 percent are troubled by the
conflict between the ruling and opposition parties, as well as an
unclear cross-strait situation.
</P>
<P>
The respondents said the three biggest challenges facing Taiwan
are inconsistent government policies with too many restrictions,
uncertain cross-strait relations and marginalization.
</P>
